Here's an example of how you can create a simple search bar using PHP:

**index.php**
```php
<?php
// Connect to database (assuming MySQL)
$conn = new mysqli("localhost", "username", "password", "database");

if ($conn->connect_error) {
    die("Connection failed: " . $conn->connect_error);
}

?>
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Search Bar</title>
    <style>
        /* Add some basic styling to the search bar */
        #search-bar {
            width: 50%;
            padding: 10px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            border-radius: 5px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <form action="<?php echo $_SERVER['PHP_SELF']; ?>" method="get">
        <!-- Search bar input field -->
        <input type="text" id="search-bar" name="q" placeholder="Search...">

        <!-- Submit button to send search query -->
        <button type="submit">Search</button>
    </form>

    <?php
    // Check if a search query has been sent
    if (isset($_GET['q'])) {
        $query = $_GET['q'];
        $sql = "SELECT * FROM table_name WHERE column_name LIKE '%$query%'";

        // Execute the SQL query and store results in an array
        $result = mysqli_query($conn, $sql);

        // Display search results
        echo "<h2>Search Results:</h2>";
        while ($row = mysqli_fetch_array($result)) {
            echo "<p>" . $row['column_name'] . "</p>";
        }
    }

    // Close database connection
    $conn->close();
    ?>
</body>
</html>
```
**Explanation:**

1. We first connect to our MySQL database using the `mysqli` extension.
2. In the HTML part, we create a simple form with an input field for the search query and a submit button.
3. When the form is submitted (i.e., when the user clicks the submit button), we check if a search query has been sent via the `$_GET['q']` superglobal variable.
4. If a search query has been sent, we construct an SQL query to select all columns from a table where a specific column contains the search query as a substring (using the `%LIKE%` operator).
5. We execute the SQL query and store the results in an array using `mysqli_query()` and `mysqli_fetch_array()`.
6. Finally, we display the search results using a simple `while` loop.

**Note:**

* Make sure to replace `"table_name"` and `"column_name"` with your actual table and column names.
* This example uses the `get` method for submitting the form, which sends the search query as part of the URL. If you prefer to use the `post` method, change the `method` attribute in the `<form>` tag to `"post"`.
* Also, this is a very basic example and may not meet your specific requirements (e.g., it doesn't handle pagination, filtering, or other advanced search features).
* As with any user-input data, be sure to sanitize and validate the search query to prevent SQL injection attacks!

